{
  "answer": "**The poem \"Abdul Qadir Ke Naam\" (Chapter 8 of *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*) is explicitly addressed to Abdul Qadir**, as indicated by its title (\"In the Name of Abdul Qadir\" or \"To Abdul Qadir\").[^1]\n\nThe poet exhorts the addressee to **arise amid encroaching darkness on the Eastern horizon and, together with the speaker, use \"fiery eloquence\" to illuminate, upend, and transform \"the assembly\" (likely a metaphor for society or a gathering)**—showing the power of love, forging the present into the future, evoking prophetic visions (e.g., Joseph and Zulaikha, Layla and Qais), teaching growth, and burning like a candle to reveal inner truth.[^2][^3]\n\n[^1]: Allama Iqbal, *Bang-E-Dara Part 2*, Chapter 8 (\"Abdul Qadir Ke Naam\"), [translation](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/08-abdul-qadir-ke-naam/translation/).\n\n[^2]: Ibid., [p-65bf0c](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/08-abdul-qadir-ke-naam/translation/#p-65bf0c).\n\n[^3]: Ibid., [full chapter](https://falsafa-corpus.com/works/allama-iqbal-bang-e-dara-part-2-9bc58c/08-abdul-qadir-ke-naam/translation/).",
